<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: CANDIDATE FINED FOR FALSE ADVERTISING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Ventura County Superior Court judge has ordered a candidate for county clerk 
to pay a $2,500 fine for falsely and deceptively advertising his business 
services, putting an end to a four-year legal dispute. 
</P>
<P>
 Daniel J. Schmidt, a former Simi Valley resident, was charged in 1991 with 
wrongfully charging business owners for unnecessary services associated with 
refiling their business licenses.  
</P>
<P>
 The legal complaint was made by the district attorney's office on behalf of 
the county clerk. 
</P>
<P>
 Schmidt ran his own legal advertising firm that published fictitious business 
names for business owners.  
</P>
<P>
 The complaint filed against him said Schmidt wrongly implied in flyers mailed 
to thousands of businesses that it was necessary to republish information when 
their licenses were renewed with the county clerk. Business licenses must be 
renewed every five years. 
</P>
<P>
 The complaint also said that flyers mailed by Schmidt's California Legal 
Publication Office closely resembled income-tax forms, giving the impression 
that Schmidt was sanctioned by a government agency. There was no indication 
that the flyers were mailed by a private business. 
</P>
<P>
 Schmidt, now a resident of Ventura, said he had consulted with officials in 
the county clerk's office before mailing the flyers and assumed there was no 
problem. However, the clerk's office never officially approved the flyers. 
</P>
<P>
 When the clerk's office received complaints from business owners who had 
received the mailers, the district attorney filed suit against Schmidt. 
</P>
<P>
 Schmidt said the message on the flyers may have confused some recipients, but 
he never intended to mislead anyone. He said he refunded money to those who had 
filed complaints against him. 
</P>
<P>
 Schmidt is the only candidate challenging the reelection of Ventura County 
Clerk Richard Dean in the June 7 election. He said he decided to run for county 
clerk because he believes the office can be managed more efficiently. 
</P>
<P>
 But Dean said Schmidt had other motives for trying to unseat him. "I think 
it's simply a matter of retaliation and retribution." CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
