<HEADLINE>
<P>
'JUDGE SHOPPING' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Dist. Atty. Michael Bradbury has gone too far. His order that his deputies 
must disqualify Superior Court Judge Lawrence Storch in all criminal cases is 
not based upon legitimate reason.It is a selfish and childish reaction. 
</P>
<P>
 Judge Storch is a highly intelligent person. He has a fine legal education. 
His years of service have demonstrated diligence, ability and an evenhanded 
fairness that are admired by his colleagues and a large majority of the 
attorneys and litigants who have appeared in his court. 
</P>
<P>
 Dist. Atty. Bradbury is also intelligent, well-educated and competent. He 
suffers, however, from one glaring weakness. He cannot stand to lose. He flies 
into an emotional pique and seeks to disqualify a highly qualified judge for 
the sole reason that the judge, in all good conscience, does not agree with 
him. 
</P>
<P>
 This is not the first time. During the past several years a series of judges 
and commissioners have made his blacklist. He was not satisfied to seek 
amelioration by turning to the appellate court. Instead, he took the Draconian 
step of automatic blackballing, regardless of the type of case, and regardless 
of the resulting interference with orderly administration of the judicial 
system. Such "judge shopping" is inconsistent with the high standards which the 
people of Ventura County have a right to expect from their district attorney. 
</P>
<P>
 Twenty-five years ago, Ventura County Deputy Dist. Atty. Bradbury was young, 
competent, eager and a gentleman. It is regrettable that the power he achieved 
has changed him so much. Ventura County is no longer well-served. 
</P>
<P>
 ROBERT R. WILLARD 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura 
</P>
<P>
 Robert R. Willard was a Superior Court judge for Ventura County from 1964 to 
1981.  
</P>
