<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: SMOOTH, CRUNCHY OR ADDITIVE-FILLED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The U.S. Food and Drug Administration says reduced-fat peanut spreads 
developed by two major food companies cannot be called peanut butter. 
</P>
<P>
 The makers have a choice: Change the formulas or call the products something 
else. 
</P>
<P>
 The decision affects Peter Pan Smart Choice, introduced in November by Hunt & 
Wesson, and Skippy Reduced-Fat, sold since January by CPC International. 
</P>
<P>
 Under FDA standards, peanut butter must contain 90% peanuts. In the low-fat 
versions, some of the peanuts are replaced by soy protein and other 
ingredients. 
</P>
<P>
 The FDA admonished the companies that "consumers expect peanut butter products 
to be made from peanuts." 
</P>
</TEXT>
