<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHEKHOV WAS BORED TOO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The best part and valid part of Don Shirley's review of "The Wood Demon" was 
his first paragraph ("Fighting a Chekhovian 'Demon' at the Taper," April 8). 
Ah, if only Shirley had stopped there and accepted Chekhov's honesty, 
disappointment and disgust at having written a most talkative, boring play, a 
play that crawled on for more than three hours.The Chekhov experience was a 
sleeper, literally. 
</P>
<P>
 I am not critical of the acting and staging -- that was competent -- but being 
competent with a production that created a verbal sedative is not enough. 
Before the end of the third act, almost half of the audience was asleep and 
most of the others had gone home. 
</P>
<P>
 By the way, the headline could be accepted as valid -- "Fighting a Chekhovian 
'Demon' at the Taper." Yes, the audience was fighting the "Demon" as long as it 
could, as long as it could keep its eyes open, and then, of course, it lost the 
fight. 
</P>
<P>
 ARTHUR SARNA 
</P>
<P>
 Sherman Oaks 
</P>
</TEXT>
