<HEADLINE>
<P>
WILSON AIDE GETS 10 DAYS FOR DRUNK DRIVING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Gov. Pete Wilson's campaign press secretary was sentenced Friday to 10 days in 
jail, fined $1,500 and placed on four years probation after pleading no contest 
to his second drunk driving offense in three years. 
</P>
<P>
 Dan Schnur, 30, also had his license suspended for one year and was ordered to 
attend a mandatory education program for those convicted of driving under the 
influence of alcohol, for which he must pay tuition of $1,500. 
</P>
<P>
 Schnur was arrested early March 5 as he was driving home from a restaurant a 
few blocks from the state Capitol. Two breath tests showed his blood-alcohol 
level to be at least 0.13%, far above the legal limit for driving of 0.08%. 
Schnur's first drunk driving conviction was in January, 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 He will spend 48 hours in Sacramento County Jail and serve the rest of his 
sentence on a county work crew, Schnur said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Alan Ziegaus, campaign communications director, said Schnur will keep his 
position. 
</P>
