<HEADLINE>
<P>
1993-94 TIMES ALL-VALLEY GIRLS' BASKETBALL TEAM; PLAYER OF THE YEAR; RIGLEY 
TOOK CONTROL TO RESCUE ALEMANY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KENNEDY COSGROVE, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 One need only look at a one-minute stretch to understand Samantha Rigley's 
value to the Alemany High basketball team. 
</P>
<P>
 Cut to the Southern Section Division II-A championship game against San 
Bernardino. 
</P>
<P>
 The Indians are undefeated and have barely been challenged all season. They 
have a comfortable lead over the Cardinals until the end of the third quarter, 
when ultra-quick San Bernardino guard LaTonya Kindle catches fire and sparks a 
comeback. 
</P>
<P>
 Twice in a row Kindle steals the ball from Alemany's point guard and scores on 
breakaway layups. 
</P>
<P>
 In a flash, Alemany's lead is cut to three points and the Indians are visibly 
shaken. 
</P>
<P>
 Except for Rigley. 
</P>
<P>
 The 5-foot-10 forward inbounds the ball and immediately demands it back. She 
will bring the ball up the floor. Kindle is all over her, itching for a steal. 
Rigley shields her away, fakes her once, twice, three times, daring Kindle. 
</P>
<P>
 After about 15 seconds, Kindle finally fouls her, and Rigley makes both free 
throws. 
</P>
<P>
 Thirty seconds later, Rigley burns Kindle with a cross-over dribble at 
midcourt, another fake in the lane and makes a tough layup with her left hand. 
</P>
<P>
 Alemany leads by seven and hangs on for the victory. 
</P>
<P>
 That's the bottom line with Rigley, whose determination and refusal to lose 
are at least as valuable as her pinpoint passing and clutch free-throw 
shooting. 
</P>
<P>
 "She is not afraid to compete, and the kids are very confident in her," Coach 
Melissa Hearlihy said. "They're always looking to give her the ball." 
</P>
<P>
 Rigley, a junior who often ran the offense, was selected to the all-state 
third team. 
</P>
<P>
 Her versatility was evident in her statistics. She averaged 14.8 points, six 
rebounds, four assists and three steals a game. 
</P>
<P>
 She also made 86.7% of her free throws. Her clutch shooting at the line was an 
anchor the team could cling to late in games. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think it's been my best year at Alemany," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 It certainly was an unforgettable season. Her family's home was red-tagged 
after the Jan. 17 earthquake -- repairs have not yet begun -- and Rigley was 
shaken by the closure of her school. 
</P>
<P>
 She was also deeply upset with the Indians' 46-41 loss to Woodbridge in the 
state semifinal, one game shy of the team's goal of the state championship. 
</P>
<P>
 "We had set our sights on state, and nothing else seemed as important," she 
said. "(Winning the section championship) was a big accomplishment, but I don't 
think we even realized what happened. 
</P>
<P>
 "But now when I think about it, I'm totally happy." Girls' Basketball Team 
</P>
<P>
 Anna Celaya / G 
</P>
<P>
 Junior / North Hollywood 
</P>
<P>
 The Huskies' steadiest player, the 5-foot-4 Celaya averaged 20.8 points and 
5.3 assists, both tops in the Mid-Valley League. She was the league co-most 
valuable player for the second consecutive season, sharing the honor with 
teammate Darvena Merritt. 
</P>
<P>
 Carly Funicello / C 
</P>
<P>
 Sophomore / Alemany 
</P>
<P>
 Funicello has remarkable agility for a 6-3 post player. She led the Indians 
with a 16-point average, grabbed nine rebounds a game and was named the state's 
sophomore player of the year. Still learning the game, she possesses enviable 
potential. 
</P>
<P>
 Sarah Hagman / G 
</P>
<P>
 Senior / Crescenta Valley 
</P>
<P>
 Hagman set Southern Section records with 13 three-point baskets in a game and 
121 for the season. She also was the top girls' scorer in the area with 25.4 
points a game. She led the Falcons to the Pacific League title and will play 
for Cal State Northridge. 
</P>
<P>
 Lindy James / F 
</P>
<P>
 Sophomore / Village Christian 
</P>
<P>
 James, a returning All-Valley selection, led the Crusaders to the Southern 
Section Division IV-A final. She was the team leader in scoring and rebounding, 
averaging 17 points and 9.5 rebounds. She scored a career-high 33 points in the 
section title game. 
</P>
<P>
 Jaclyn Johnson / C 
</P>
<P>
 Freshman / Quartz Hill 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson is a prodigious talent -- and didn't turn 15 until last month. She was 
the best player for the Golden League champion Rebels (19-5), who advanced to 
the Southern Section Division I-A quarterfinals. The 6-footer averaged 18 
points and 12 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
 Kelly McKay / G 
</P>
<P>
 Junior / Alemany 
</P>
<P>
 McKay's quiet, controlled demeanor proved that actions speak louder than 
words. The 5-8 shooting guard was Alemany's best defender and smoothest player. 
McKay, who was named to the all-state junior team, averaged 13.8 points and 
four steals. 
</P>
<P>
 Samantha Rigley / F 
</P>
<P>
 Junior / Alemany 
</P>
<P>
 The player of the year led the Indians (30-1) to the Southern Section Division 
II-A championship. The versatile 5-10 Rigley averaged 14.8 points, six 
rebounds, four assists and three steals. She was selected to the all-state 
third team. 
</P>
<P>
 Nadra Manley / F 
</P>
<P>
 Junior / Sylmar 
</P>
<P>
 Manley led the Spartans to their best season in school history as Sylmar 
(18-3) advanced to the City Section 3-A Division quarterfinals. Manley was 
named the East Valley League's most valuable player and averaged a team-high 18 
points. 
</P>
<P>
 Brandee Sayles / F 
</P>
<P>
 Senior / Antelope Valley 
</P>
<P>
 Sayles stood out on a poor team and was named the Golden League's most 
valuable player. The 5-9 swing player averaged 22 points, 11.5 rebounds and 5.6 
assists. She possesses an excellent mid-range jump shot and is equally adept 
driving to the basket. 
</P>
<P>
 Christina Ticsay / G 
</P>
<P>
 Senior / Bell-Jeff 
</P>
<P>
 Ticsay, hampered her sophomore and junior seasons by a skin disorder that 
caused her body hair to fall out, enjoyed a memorable senior season. Her 
disorder was controlled by medication, and she averaged a team-high 19.5 points 
and six assists. Times' All-Star Basketball Rosters 
</P>
